User observed JSWINFRA showing Dec 2025 / Q3 FY26 as latest in the
report when the company had already filed Q4 FY26 (Mar 2026 quarter).
Footer was 'financials: screener_in', meaning the NSE override never
fired — Screener was lagging and our code didn't catch up.

Two root causes:
1. NSE override required ≥4 quarters before activating. Many smaller
   caps (especially recent IPOs) have 1-3 NSE filings indexed; we'd
   skip NSE entirely even when its single most-recent row was newer
   than Screener's stale latest.
2. fetchCompanyFinancialResults made one bare-symbol call to NSE
   without a date range. Some symbols return ancient cached results
   from that endpoint.

Fixes:
- Lower override threshold from 4 → 1 NSE quarter. Any NSE row that
  passes the 60-130 day single-quarter filter is now spliced into
  the merged quarterly array.
- Add a 'freshness patch' detection: parse Screener's period labels
  ('Mar 2025') back into timestamps; if NSE's latest period is more
  recent than Screener's, log it explicitly in debug.warnings so
  users can see why the source flipped.
- Merge logic now sorts the union of NSE + Screener-only periods by
  parsed timestamp and takes the most recent 12. Earlier code only
  appended NSE rows after Screener-only rows, which broke if NSE
  filled a period that fell between two Screener rows.
- fetchCompanyFinancialResults: now hits NSE twice in fallback —
  first with Quarterly + 3y date range (last 36 months), then
  bare-symbol as backup. Results are merged + deduped by
  (toDate × consolidated/standalone). Smaller caps that don't
  respond to date filter still work via fallback.
- Return type made explicit Promise<any> so the existing
  Array.isArray / .data handling at call sites doesn't narrow.

After deploy, JSWINFRA should show Mar 2026 / Q4 FY26 as latest if
NSE has filed it; if NSE also lags, the report falls back to Screener
with a debug note about the freshness gap.

